To confirm the type of surface defect (Zn vacancies or S vacancies), some STEM images of 0.3ZCS (Fig. 4
                        ) are measured by spherical aberration electron microscope. From Fig. 4a and b, the defect sites are obvious (marked with yellow shapes), with some atoms missing. If there is no defect (Fig. 4c), the lattice atoms are relatively orderly arranged. To verify the defect type, the STEM images (Fig. S3) and corresponding EDS spectra of 0.3ZCS with and without defects are measured. From the atomic percentage of 0.3ZCS (Zn: Cd in EDS spectra), the Zn ratio with defect sites is lower than that of no defect sites. This indicates that the missing atom are mainly Zn atoms. In addition, the element amount of 0.3ZCS samples with defect is compared with the 0.3ZCS-R without defect [40] were analyzed by inductively coupled plasma optical emission spectrometry (ICP-OES). From the molar rations (Zn: Cd: S) of ICP-OES (Table 1
                        ), the Zn ratio of 0.3ZCS with defect is much lower than 0.3ZCS-R without defect, which can confirm that the surface defects are Zn vacancies.

Another important aromatic alcohol, benzyl alcohol is also investigated, which performs similar photocatalytic results with 4-bromobenzyl alcohol (Fig. 8
                        ). H2, CO and CH4 are the main gas reduction products (Fig. 8a and b), with the generated rate of 434, 0.84 and 0.64 μmol g−1 h−1, respectively. Meanwhile, the oxidation product is benzaldehyde (PhCHO, Fig. 8b), with its rate of 470 μmol g−1 h−1. The selectivity of PhCHO is over 90 % on the whole catalysts, and no other by-products are detected (Fig. 8c). By comparison, the photocatalytic activity of benzyl alcohol is much lower than that of 4-chlorobenzyl alcohol. There may be two reasons resulted to the difference in activity, and one is the Cl atom with greater electronegativity than H in the benzene ring. When Cl replaces H, the electron cloud of the C-Cl bond is biased toward Cl. The other reason is the production of CH4, as its generation path is more complicated and need more electrons (eight electrons) to reduce CO2. To confirm this view, 4-bromobenzyl alcohol is considered with C-Br bond on the benzene ring. The photocatalytic activity is also enhanced compared with that of benzyl alcohol (Table 2
                        ).
